{% extends "layouts/forms-website.njk" %}
{% from "masthead/macro.njk" import appMasthead %}

{% block beforeContent %}
{{ appMasthead({
  heading: {
    text: "Adapting a PDF or paper form to a digital form"
  }
}) }}
{% endblock -%}

{% block content %}
<div>
  <div class="govuk-width-container">
    <div class="govuk-grid-row">
      <div class="govuk-grid-column-two-thirds">
        <div class="app-prose-scope">  
          <p>
            Most things in a paper form are simple to adapt to be easy to fill in on a computer or smartphone, but some things need to be redesigned so that people can complete them easily. This sometimes requires thinking differently about the information you need to collect.   
          </p>
        <h2>Tables</h2>
          <p>
            Some paper forms have tables in them, for users to fill in. For example, it may have been designed for fishers to record their catches throughout the year, or a farmer to declare how many different animal species, and of what type, they keep.   
          </p>
          <p>
           This makes sense when a user is looking at a paper form, but does not work when viewed on a mobile device. Tables are too wide, and the boxes too small to type into.
          </p>
          <p>
          Instead, design your form to collect the same information over a number of screens in your digital form. Think of each column or row as a separate question.
          </p>
          <p>
          Make a screen for each column or row, so users can still enter the information in a way that makes sense to them.
          </p>
          <p>
          <div>
            <img src="/assets/images/website/guidance_images/table_alternative_01.png"  class="govuk-!-width-full" alt="Diagram of the logic of conditions.">
          </div>
          </p>
          <p>
          This example shows how you can ask for how many tonnes of fish are caught in a year, by type of fish. 
          </p>
          <p>
          <div>
            <img src="/assets/images/website/guidance_images/table_alternative_02.png"  class="govuk-!-width-full" alt="Diagram of the logic of conditions.">
          </div>
          </p>
          <p>
          This example asks how much cod was caught in a year, with boxes for each month. 
          </p>
          <p>
          Ensure that all the fields are set as optional, as users may not need to put information in every one.  
          </p>
        <h2>Signatures</h2>
          <p>
            Many paper forms ask users for a signature to confirm that what they are submitting is true, and they accept any terms stated by Defra. The most efficient equivalent of this for a digital form is a declaration box that users can click to confirm they agree with the terms Defra has stated. This is a standard developed by Government Digital Service to cover most requirements for declarations from users in digital forms. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Sometimes it is thought that there is a legal or policy reason that a physical (or ‘wet’) signature is needed. This is usually not the case. Check the legislation related to the form you are creating to see if a wet signature is legally required. On the rare occasion that a wet signature is definitely needed, do not proceed with creating a digital form.  
          </p>
          <p>
            <div>
              <img src="/assets/images/website/guidance_images/declaration.png"  class="govuk-!-width-full" alt="Diagram of the logic of conditions.">
            </div> 
          </p>   
</div>
      </div>
    </div>
</div>
</div>
{% endblock %}
